Crisp air slices through the veil of night,
while dawn mist tiptoes over sleeping stones,
weaving lace on spider’s thread and root,
a spectral choir in hushed tones.

The pines inhale the chill, release a sigh,
as stars retreat to secret skies;
the moon, a smudge of fading pearl,
watches the waking world arise.

A stream, half-dreaming, laughs in ripples,
over pebbles dressed in frost;
even the wind takes off its boots,
tiptoeing through the misty host.

Here, time forgets to measure hours,
and thoughts uncurl like ferns in spring;
the mist is memory, the air a spell—
every breath a small returning.

Oh, let this moment stretch like mist,
endless, weightless, pure, and thin;
for in this dawn’s cool, quiet kiss,
the soul remembers how to begin.
